= lesson 25: numbers

== Cardinal numbers

Let's talk numbers!

#list((
  word("ůĪ•≥", "wan", "one; united"),
  word("ůĪ•ģ", "tu", "two; divided"),
  word("ůĪ§≠", "luka", "five, hand"),
  word("ůĪ§ľ", "mute", "many"),
  word("ůĪ§Ą", "ale", "all, every"),
  word("ůĪ•Ľ", "kipisi", "piece, part; to split"),
))

Toki Pona has words for 1, 2, 5, but not 3 or 4! But this is not so strange. You
can imagine #strong[ůĪ•≥ wan], #strong[ůĪ•ģ tu], #strong[ůĪ§≠ luka] like coins worth 1,
2, and 5. Let's try counting from 1 to 10:

#list((
  word("ůĪ•≥", "wan", "one"),
  word("ůĪ•ģ", "tu", "two"),
  word("ůĪ•ģůĪ•≥", "tu wan", "three"),
  word("ůĪ•ģůĪ•ģ", "tu tu", "four"),
  word("ůĪ§≠", "luka", "five"),
  word("ůĪ§≠ůĪ•≥", "luka wan", "six"),
  word("ůĪ§≠ůĪ•ģ", "luka tu", "seven"),
  word("ůĪ§≠ůĪ•ģůĪ•≥", "luka tu wan", "eight"),
  word("ůĪ§≠ůĪ•ģůĪ•ģ", "luka tu tu", "nine"),
  word("ůĪ§≠ůĪ§≠", "luka luka", "ten"),
))

In many situations, just knowing small numbers will be enough. But if you want
to talk about purchases or the Gregorian calendar, there's an extra page about
large numbers below.

== Ordinal numbers

Usually, numbers are just adjectives:

#list((
  word("ůĪ§ĒůĪ•≥", "kala wan", "one fish"),
  word("ůĪ¶ĀůĪ•ģůĪ•ģ", "soko tu tu", "four mushrooms"),
  word("ůĪ§ļůĪ§≠", "mun luka", "five months"),
))

But these are #emph[cardinal] numbers: numbers that talk about quantity. There
are also #emph[ordinal] numbers: those that talk about order. To make ordinal
numbers, just use #strong[ůĪ§Ĺ nanpa] + a number:

#list((
  word("ůĪ§Ĺ", "nanpa", "number; the ...-th"),
  word("ůĪ§ĒůĪ§ĹůĪ•≥", "kala nanpa wan", "the first fish"),
  word("ůĪ¶ĀůĪ§ĹůĪ•ģůĪ•ģ", "soko nanpa tu tu", "the fourth mushroom"),
  word("ůĪ§ļůĪ§ĹůĪ§≠", "mun nanpa luka", "the fifth month"),
))

(By the way, #strong[ůĪ§Ĺ nanpa] is special! It doesn't need #strong[ůĪ•ć pi].)

